      MoviePass
   =20
 =20
Obviously=C2=A0if MoviePass hadn=E2=80=99t gone bankrupt in January 2020, b=
ut had instead limped along until January 2021, it would be a $50 billion c=
ompany right now. How could it not have become a meme stock? It has everyth=
ing. Its product =E2=80=94=C2=A0you pay MoviePass $10 a month, and in excha=
nge you can see as many movies as you want, in theaters =E2=80=94=C2=A0has =
the retail-focused, nostalgic, pandemic-scarred appeal of other meme stocks=
 like AMC Entertainment Holdings Inc. and GameStop Corp. Also its business =
model made no sense: You could see all those movies because MoviePass would=
 buy tickets for you, at full price, generally $10 a ticket or more; it los=
t money on most of its customers every month. This led people to short the =
company (technically its parent company, Helios & Matheson Analytics Inc.),=
 which would no doubt have infuriated Reddit meme-stock traders and led the=
m to short-squeeze it.Also I guess =E2=80=A6=C2=A0I guess that Covid-19 wou=
ld have been really good for MoviePass? Its main risk was that people would=
 use its product, and in a pandemic they=E2=80=99d have to stop. (For a whi=
le, pre-pandemic,=C2=A0MoviePass dealt with this risk by  changing people=
=E2=80=99s passwords so they couldn=E2=80=99t use the product, an incredibl=
e power move that surely would have appealed to Reddit?) It just seems perf=
ectly set up for 2021, and it=E2=80=99s a shame we never got to see what ha=
ppened, because its business model=C2=A0 did not work, it ran out of money,=
 and Helios & Matheson filed for bankruptcy in 2020.=C2=A0Back in the day, =
I wrote admiringly about MoviePass because it seemed so crazy, a leading ex=
ample of how late-2010s consumer services were uneconomically subsidized by=
 growth-hungry investors. (=E2=80=9CThe MoviePass Economy,=E2=80=9D we call=
ed it.)=C2=A0But MoviePass was a symbol of wild incomprehensibility back in=
 what was, in retrospect, a fairly comprehensible time. In 2021 every singl=
e thing that I write about makes less sense than MoviePass. =E2=80=9CBuy un=
limited $10 movie tickets and give them to people for a $10 monthly fee=E2=
=80=9D? Sure yeah that sounds fine, have you heard about NFTs?Anyway it=E2=
=80=99s back:MoviePass cofounder Stacy Spikes was granted ownership of the =
company by a Southern District of New York bankruptcy court judge who appro=
ved the sale on [last]=C2=A0Monday, according to court documents reviewed b=
y Insider. The financial transaction took place on Wednesday.Spikes had pla=
ced a bid of an undisclosed amount to the trustee handling the bankruptcy o=
f Helios and Matheson Analytics (HMNY), the former parent company of MovieP=
ass."I can confirm that we acquired MoviePass out of bankruptcy on Wednesda=
y," Spikes said in a statement to Insider. "We are thrilled to have it back=
 and are exploring the possibility of relaunching soon. Our pursuit to recl=
aim the brand was encouraged by the continued interest from the moviegoing =
community. We believe, if done properly, theatrical subscription can play a=
n instrumental role in lifting moviegoing attendance to new heights." ...Sp=
ikes hopes to relaunch MoviePass sometime next year.=C2=A0A new site has be=
en created for the relaunch, iwantmoviepass.com, and its logo will now feat=
ure a black background with white lettering, ditching its previous red back=
ground. Here is the new logo:The new logo is somehow not a picture of Doge.=
 He=E2=80=99d better be selling non-fungible tokens of movie tickets. He=E2=
=80=99d better be teaming up with AMC to get people free MoviePass shares w=
ith  a large popcorn. He=E2=80=99d better be launching his own cryptocurren=
cy. There=E2=80=99d better be an  electric-vehicle angle in there somewhere=
.=C2=A0Sure=C2=A0financial news in 2021 has been dumb, but it has been miss=
ing MoviePass. Now it=E2=80=99s perfect.
