One theory you could have about environmental, social and governance invest=
ing is that it is a good investing=C2=A0strategy; it maximizes expected ret=
urns. Coolly self-interested investors say to themselves =E2=80=9Cif we don=
=E2=80=99t reduce carbon emissions and racial inequalities, we will make le=
ss money, so we should do those things.=E2=80=9D This is a real theory that=
 people very much believe in, though there are also doubters.Another theory=
 you could have about ESG is that it is a good=C2=A0marketing=C2=A0strategy=
; it maximizes the ability of institutional asset managers to gather assets=
. Coolly self-interested asset managers say to themselves =E2=80=9Cif we te=
ll people that we are reducing carbon emissions and racial inequalities, th=
ey will give us their money to manage.=E2=80=9D There is some obvious truth=
 to this one, and you don=E2=80=99t have to be cynical about it; big asset =
managers do say that their ESG concerns=C2=A0are=C2=A0client-driven, and ge=
nerally it is good for asset managers to do what clients want. (This theory=
 pushes down the question of, well, why do the clients want it?)A third the=
ory you could have about ESG is that it is a good=C2=A0personal=C2=A0strate=
gy: Investors are people, they live on a planet and in a society, they want=
 the planet to be habitable and the society to be good, investment returns =
are not everything.What do you make of this?A decade ago, the hottest M.B.A=
. courses typically covered topics such as game theory, valuing securities =
and negotiating mergers. Today, some of the most popular classes are about =
climate finance, impact investing and social entrepreneurship.The Universit=
y of Pennsylvania Wharton School of Business now offers more than 50 underg=
raduate and graduate courses related to social impact. The Duke University =
Fuqua School of Business recently added a course to its core curriculum cal=
led =E2=80=9CBusiness and Common Purpose.=E2=80=9D At Harvard Business Scho=
ol, 600 students took second-year elective courses related to social enterp=
rise last year, compared with 251 in 2012.=E2=80=9CThere=E2=80=99s been an =
explosion of interest from students,=E2=80=9D said Todd Cort, a lecturer on=
 sustainability at the Yale School of Management and the co-director of the=
 school=E2=80=99s environment and business center.This interest reflects an=
 increase in jobs that require knowledge in environmental, social and gover=
nance, or E.S.G., topics.Global sustainable investment topped $30 trillion =
in 2019 =E2=80=94 up 68 percent since 2014, according to McKinsey. That has=
 created more jobs in the field, which has pushed salaries higher for worke=
rs with the necessary skills. In addition, companies say they=E2=80=99re ha=
ving an easier time recruiting junior employees than senior leaders in E.S.=
G. roles, which could give younger workers an advantage in climbing the cor=
porate ladder (or allow them to start at a higher rung) than for the typica=
l jobs for M.B.A. graduates.You could tell a marketing story here: ESG inve=
sting is hot, so business school students want to market themselves to empl=
oyers by taking ESG courses. You could tell an investing-returns story here=
: ESG investing is hot because it works, so business schools on the cutting=
 edge of financial research teach it as a way to maximize long-term returns=
. You could tell a personal story here: Young people in business school are=
 relatively idealistic (compared to grizzled financial veterans, I mean, no=
t compared to, like, young people in social work school), and they are the =
paying consumers of business education, so they want classes that align wit=
h their personal morality.One other story I would tell is one of intellectu=
al frameworks. We  talked a few years ago about a paper finding that changi=
ng academic views about the benefits of conglomerates in business schools l=
ed, a decade or two later, to changes in how businesses were run: Chief exe=
cutive officers who were taught in business school that diversification and=
 conglomeration were good ended up building conglomerates, while CEOs who w=
ere taught that they were bad ended up dismantling them. I wrote that this =
was kind of a nice result:It says something nice about the value of teacher=
s and scholars, for one thing. But it also says something nice about CEOs. =
It suggests that they want to do the right thing, and they have a socially =
developed framework for deciding what the right thing is, and that framewor=
k changes over time for intellectual reasons rather than just because of co=
nstraints and incentives. There is really nothing weird or surprising about=
 that, but it just tends not to be how corporate-finance theory works.Why a=
re business schools teaching dozens of ESG courses? Maybe because that=E2=
=80=99s the cutting edge of financial return maximization, maybe because it=
=E2=80=99s what employers want for market reasons, maybe because it=E2=80=
=99s what students want for personal reasons. But they=C2=A0are=C2=A0teachi=
ng lots of ESG courses, which means that if you go to business school now y=
ou=E2=80=99ll get a lot of ESG in your curriculum. Probably that will affec=
t how you think companies should be run, and how you eventually run compani=
es yourself.
