      The Elon show
   =20
 =20
Elon Musk keeps selling Tesla Inc. shares and I suppose I=E2=80=99m obliged=
 to keep up to date on that?=C2=A0We have discussed it previously=C2=A0 her=
e and  here. There are two strands of Musk-selling-Tesla things that seem t=
o be going on these days:=09He has 22.9 million stock options that expire n=
ext August. He has previously said that he was going to exercise all of tho=
se options and sell roughly half the underlying shares to pay taxes, all wi=
thin the fourth quarter of 2021. He has an automatic Rule 10b5-1 plan, whic=
h he set up in September, to do some or all of that option-exercising and s=
tock-selling. Last Monday, the automatic plan exercised 2.15 million option=
s and sold 934,091 shares. That was the first, and so far the last, that=C2=
=A0we heard of it.[1]=09As of last weekend (Nov. 6), he owned between 170 m=
illion and 244 million shares of Tesla stock, depending how you count. (Dep=
ending whether you count only shares he owns outright, or also shares under=
lying options.) On Nov. 6, he asked Twitter if he should sell 10% of those =
shares for no particular reason. (I mean, the stated reason was something l=
ike =E2=80=9Cshould I voluntarily trigger a few billion dollars of capital-=
gains taxes for trolling purposes?=E2=80=9D) He took a poll, he promised to=
 abide by the results of the poll,=C2=A058% of votes were for =E2=80=9Cyes,=
=E2=80=9D and off he went selling stock. He started last Tuesday, and by Fr=
iday he had sold about 5.4 million shares for about $5.8 billion. Here I am=
 not counting the 934,091 shares that he sold in Strand 1; the shares sold =
in Strand 2 were not the results of new=C2=A0option exercises.[2]So where a=
re we? Last week Musk sold a total of about 6.4 million Tesla shares for ab=
out $6.9 billion. On Strand 1,=C2=A0I would naively assume that Musk will e=
xercise another 20.7 million options, and sell another 10-million-ish share=
s, automatically under his 10b5-1=C2=A0plan in the next six weeks. But ther=
e=E2=80=99s no guarantee of that. Maybe the 10b5-1 plan runs through next y=
ear, or maybe it only exercises if the stock price is above a certain level=
, and it won=E2=80=99t actually do the whole 20.7 million. Maybe he cancele=
d the 10b5-1 plan after Monday=E2=80=99s sales to focus more on his trollin=
g. Who knows!=C2=A0On Strand 2, I=E2=80=99m assuming he will sell at least =
11.6 million more shares, to get to 17 million, which represents roughly 10=
% of the shares he had when he tweeted the poll. I assume he will do that f=
airly quickly; at roughly his current clip, that means something like anoth=
er two or three weeks to get through the full 17 million. But, again, who k=
nows!The simplest possibility is that his Strand 2 selling =E2=80=94=C2=A0j=
ust selling shares he already owns=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0will raise enough ca=
sh to pay his taxes on the stock-option exercise, so that he doesn=E2=80=99=
t need to do any more Strand 1 selling. If he sells 17 million shares he wi=
ll collect, let=E2=80=99s say, $18 billion.[3] That would incur taxes of pe=
rhaps $4 billion, leaving him with perhaps $14 billion of net proceeds.[4] =
If he then exercises his remaining 20.7 million options, he=E2=80=99ll have=
 taxable income of something like $21.3 billion.[5] He has said he pays a 5=
3% income tax rate, so he=E2=80=99ll owe about $11.3 billion more in taxes.=
 His sales will cover that with a couple billion dollars left over. This is=
 not the traditional way to pay taxes on options exercise =E2=80=94=C2=A0th=
e traditional way is what he did last Monday, exercising and selling a port=
ion of the underlying shares =E2=80=94=C2=A0but, you know, also fine.[6]=C2=
=A0Anyway on Saturday Bernie Sanders tweeted something=C2=A0anodyne about h=
ow rich people should pay taxes, and Musk got mad on Twitter and offered to=
 sell more stock. =E2=80=9CWant me to sell more stock, Bernie? Just say the=
 word =E2=80=A6,=E2=80=9D he tweeted. Sanders should do it! =E2=80=9CSure E=
lon, sell another 30 million,=E2=80=9D why not, see if it works.The stock w=
as down about 4% as of 11 a.m. today; it=E2=80=99s down about 19% since Nov=
. 5, the last trading day before Musk=E2=80=99s poll. In general it is my t=
heory that when Musk is loud, annoying and funny on Twitter, that is good f=
or Tesla=E2=80=99s stock price; that attracts the attention of loyal fans w=
ho will bid up the stock. But it is not working here, I suppose for the obv=
ious reason that the particular loud, annoying, funny thing that Musk is do=
ing on Twitter is dumping billions of dollars of Tesla stock. One lesson he=
re is that if Musk wants to tank Tesla=E2=80=99s stock =E2=80=94=C2=A0by=C2=
=A0talking constantly for a week about how he=E2=80=99s selling it=C2=A0=E2=
=80=94=C2=A0he can do it. Why does he want to?
