   =20
      Fiduciaries
   =20
 =20
Honestly it=E2=80=99s a little weird that Meta Platforms Inc. (sorry! that =
means Facebook!) board member Peter Thiel is trying to  break up Meta Platf=
orms Inc. from the outside?Ohio Senate candidate JD Vance says his Silicon =
Valley experience makes him ideal to take on big technology companies, a fa=
vorite target of Republicans, but he=E2=80=99ll have to brush off attacks f=
rom rivals who question his sincerity on tech issues. =E2=80=A6Vance, a Yal=
e Law School graduate, argues that his background in technology makes him b=
est equipped to dismantle the =E2=80=9Cbig tech oligarchy.=E2=80=9D Yet his=
 connections invite attacks from rivals as someone who made his money in Si=
licon Valley and is backed by a super political action committee that recei=
ved $10 million from technology billionaire Peter Thiel. =E2=80=A6As part o=
f his bid to replace retiring Senator Rob Portman, Vance advocates for brea=
king up companies including Alphabet Inc.=E2=80=99s Google, Meta Platforms =
Inc., the company formerly known as Facebook, Twitter Inc., Amazon.com, and=
 Apple Inc., because they=E2=80=99re =E2=80=9Cway too powerful for the comm=
on good.=E2=80=9DHow do you parse that? Thiel is putting a portion of his t=
ime and personal fortune into backing efforts to break up Meta and make it =
less powerful. What could that mean for his service on Meta=E2=80=99s board=
? Some possibilities:=09Thiel believes that breaking up Meta and making it =
less powerful would be good for Meta shareholders, so it is consistent with=
 his fiduciary duties to try to break it up and limit its power.=C2=A0This =
is counterintuitive but I kind of like it; I have   argued before that shar=
eholders now=C2=A0want=C2=A0companies to put society=E2=80=99s interests ab=
ove their own. But is Thiel advocating for a breakup at Meta board meetings=
? Has he been shot down by other board members with a shorter-term focus? H=
as he considered going public with his concerns? Or has he not actually pus=
hed for this change, which he considers good, from the inside?=09Thiel beli=
eves that breaking up Meta would be=C2=A0bad=C2=A0for Meta shareholders, an=
d so as a Meta board member he has not advocated for that, but when he leav=
es the boardroom he devotes a lot of his time and money to that cause. That=
 seems like a bad thing for a fiduciary to do! I suppose it is=C2=A0possibl=
e=C2=A0that, in his capacity as a Meta board member, he does everything in =
his power to help shareholders, and he carefully divides his helping-shareh=
olders in the boardroom from his hurting-shareholders outside of it. Still =
it feels like Meta could probably get directors who spend none of their tim=
e=C2=A0trying=C2=A0to hurt its shareholders?=09I suppose I have to put the =
words =E2=80=9CStraussian reading=E2=80=9D here somewhere. One version of t=
hat is: Thiel thinks that saying =E2=80=9CI will break up Facebook=E2=80=9D=
 is a winning electoral strategy,[8]=C2=A0and that the candidates he backs =
will say it but not do it, and then they=E2=80=99ll get elected and do othe=
r things he wants without actually breaking up Meta. This is, I suppose, el=
ectorally=C2=A0distasteful but fine as a matter of Thiel=E2=80=99s fiduciar=
y duties. Or perhaps he thinks they might do it but the risk of that to Met=
a is small, while the benefits of them doing other things are large.=C2=A0O=
ne of  my great themes around here is that, if you try hard enough, you can=
 transform basically anything you dislike into a shareholder lawsuit. I fee=
l like there has to be a Meta shareholder who dislikes Thiel=E2=80=99s poli=
tics and can make some hay with this.
