 =20
Pfizer Fights to Control Secret of $36 Billion Covid Vaccine Recipe. M.B.A.=
 Starting Salaries Are Soaring. Private equity buyers plot to carve up Gene=
ral Electric. Crypto prime brokerage. Bitcoin Creator Satoshi Nakamoto Coul=
d Be Unmasked at Florida Trial. Debit cards are hidden financial infrastruc=
ture. A  $27 Billion Token Loved by Exiled Billionaire and Steve Bannon.  A=
rgentina Bonds Climb as President Promises New Plan After Vote. Jes Staley =
exchanged 1,200 emails with Epstein that included unexplained phrases. Chin=
a Bought Italian Military-Drone Maker Without Authorities=E2=80=99 Knowledg=
e. The Coach Who Led the U.S. Math Team Back to the Top. =E2=80=9CAn online=
 dating service targeting Harvard students was recently revealed to be an e=
laborate prank and the brainchild of an MIT student.=E2=80=9D The new Russi=
an fighter jet has a perfume.If you'd like to get=C2=A0Money=C2=A0Stuff=C2=
=A0in handy email form, right in your inbox, please=C2=A0subscribe at this =
link. Or you can subscribe to Money Stuff and other great Bloomberg newslet=
ters here. Thanks![1] One weird note about the 10b5-1 plan. The way  10b5-1=
 plans work is that when an executive of a public company does=C2=A0not=C2=
=A0have any material nonpublic information, she can set up a 10b5-1 plan to=
 automatically sell (or buy) stock in the future. Then, when the 10b5-1 pla=
n sells stock, she will not get in trouble for insider trading, even if at=
=C2=A0that=C2=A0point she has material nonpublic information. Generally the=
re's a convention that executives are in an =E2=80=9Copen window=E2=80=9D f=
or at least a few weeks shortly after announcing earnings: Right after earn=
ings, the market supposedly knows everything the company does, and so execu=
tives can trade or set up 10b5-1 plans. Now, I  pointed out last week that =
Musk is apparently in an open window right now. (That's how he can dump all=
 the stock from Strand 2, which does not involve a 10b5-1 plan.) But a read=
er emailed me to point out that, when Musk set up this 10b5-1 plan on Sept.=
 14, he =E2=80=A6 arguably =E2=80=A6 was not? I mean, =E2=80=9Copen window=
=E2=80=9D is a vague concept. But Sept. 14 was about two weeks before the e=
nd of the third quarter, a time when many companies consider their executiv=
es to be =E2=80=9Cin blackout=E2=80=9D and not allowed to trade. Also the t=
hird quarter of 2021 =E2=80=94=C2=A0the one that ended two weeks after he s=
et up the 10b5-1 plan =E2=80=94=C2=A0was Tesla=E2=80=99s best ever. Weird t=
o set up a 10b5-1 plan then, just *before* earnings.=C2=A0[2] One technical=
 note. When we last discussed this, last Thursday, Musk owned shares in two=
 different forms. At the close of trading on Nov. 10, he owned 166,904,938 =
shares in the name of The Elon Musk Revocable Trust, which is how he normal=
ly owns all his shares, and 1,220,481 shares in his own name, which he got =
from exercising options last Monday. At some point that evening, I guess, h=
e transferred the 1.2 million personal shares to his trust, leaving him wit=
h 168,125,419 shares in the trust, which he then kept selling the next day.=
 This is mentioned in note 2 to the first Form 4 he filed on Friday. Whethe=
r he sold those 1.2 million shares on Thursday or Friday (as opposed to sel=
ling shares he owned earlier) I don=E2=80=99t know, but they were his highe=
st-basis shares (he already paid taxes on them in the options exercise) so =
I assume so? But this whole thing was a tax-trolling exercise, so who knows=
.=C2=A0[3] Real casual math here. He=E2=80=99s collected $6.9 billion from =
selling 6,361,875 shares. I assume his target is 17,049,299 shares, 10% of =
his holdings as of Nov. 6 (before this all started). That leaves him 10,687=
,424=C2=A0more shares. The lowest average daily price that he got for his s=
hares was $1,029 this past Friday; I just multiply that by the remaining sh=
ares to get $11 billion more proceeds. The share number is uncertain and th=
e sales price is of course totally unknown at this point; if he keeps selli=
ng millions of shares that might drive the price down. But at this point ev=
eryone knows it=E2=80=99s coming.[4] The top federal long-term capital gain=
s rate is effectively 23.8%. I assume his basis in most of these shares is =
essentially zero. However, I would guess that his basis on about 1.2 millio=
n shares would be essentially his sale price (or higher); see footnote 2. S=
o not quite 23.8% of $18 billion; call it $4 billion.[5] The income is the =
price of the stock at exercise minus the strike price of the options ($6.24=
). I assume the stock is worth $1,033.42, the closing price on Friday, thou=
gh of course that will move. So $21.3 billion of taxable gains, taxed at 53=
% is $11.3 billion.[6] One reason it=E2=80=99s not traditional is that, doi=
ng it this way, you get taxed twice: He pays capital gains on the (long-hel=
d, low-basis) shares that he sells, and then pays income tax on option exer=
cise. If you do the normal approach, you pay income tax on the exercise but=
 no tax on the shares you sell (because your basis in them is basically the=
 sales price, as opposed to selling the long-held low-basis shares). This s=
aves you taxes =E2=80=94=C2=A0in my rough numbers, it would save Musk about=
 $4 billion. But the trade-off is that if he does this, Musk ends up with 2=
0.7 million shares with high ($1,000-ish) basis, which is not nothing. Trad=
itionally you=E2=80=99re supposed to defer taxes as long as possible but if=
 you=E2=80=99re Elon Musk perhaps you don=E2=80=99t care that much.[7] Trea=
sury bill rates these days are in the ballpark of 5 to 7 basis points. If y=
ou kept those returns, had zero expenses, and ran a minimum 4% leverage rat=
io, you=E2=80=99d get a return on equity of about 1.25% or so: You=E2=80=99=
d put up $40 million of your own money to run a billion-dollar stablecoin, =
and in return you=E2=80=99d get about $500,000 a year.[8] Obviously saying =
=E2=80=9CI will break up Meta=E2=80=9D is not a winning electoral strategy =
because no one knows what Meta is. Or maybe that's good? =E2=80=9CI will br=
eak up the Galactic Spice Mining Conglomerate, which has become too powerfu=
l for the common good and created all of our modern problems.=E2=80=9D That=
=E2=80=99s=C2=A0a good pitch!
