</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Obviously=C2=A0if MoviePass hadn=E2=80=
=99t <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25710228.2786=
63/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY25uLmNvbS8yMDIwLzAxLzI5L21lZGlhL21vdmllcGFzcy1iYW5rcnVw=
dGN5L2luZGV4Lmh0bWw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6da7ab7e" itemprop=3D"StoryLin=
k" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-=
decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color:=
 #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">gone bankrup=
t in January 2020</a>, but had instead limped along until January 2021, it =
would be a $50 billion company right now. How could it not have become a me=
me stock? It has everything. Its product =E2=80=94=C2=A0you pay MoviePass $=
10 a month, and in exchange you can see as many movies as you want, in thea=
ters =E2=80=94=C2=A0has the retail-focused, nostalgic, pandemic-scarred app=
eal of other meme stocks like AMC Entertainment Holdings Inc. and GameStop =
Corp. Also its business model made no sense: You could see all those movies=
 because MoviePass would buy tickets for you, at full price, generally $10 =
a ticket or more; it lost money on most of its customers every month. This =
led people to short the company (technically its parent company, Helios &am=
p; Matheson Analytics Inc.), which would no doubt have infuriated Reddit me=
me-stock traders and led them to short-squeeze it.</p><p style=3D"margin: 1=
6px 0;">Also I guess =E2=80=A6=C2=A0I guess that Covid-19 would have been r=
eally good for MoviePass? Its main risk was that people would use its produ=
ct, and in a pandemic they=E2=80=99d have to stop. (For a while, pre-pandem=
ic,=C2=A0MoviePass dealt with this risk by <a href=3D"https://link.mail.blo=
ombergbusiness.com/click/25710228.278663/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS=
9uZXdzL25ld3NsZXR0ZXJzLzIwMjEtMDYtMDgvbW9uZXktc3R1ZmYtbW92aWVwYXNzLWNoYW5nZ=
WQtc29tZS1wYXNzd29yZHM_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTExNTIxX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1l=
bWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjExMTE1JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1=
tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4eec603f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" ite=
mscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decora=
tion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0000=
00; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> <em>changing peop=
le=E2=80=99s passwords so they couldn=E2=80=99t use the product</em></a>, a=
n incredible power move that surely would have appealed to Reddit?) It just=
 seems perfectly set up for 2021, and it=E2=80=99s a shame we never got to =
see what happened, because its business model=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.=
mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25710228.278663/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZX=
JnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTktMDgtMDcvbW92aWVwYXNzLXdvcmtlZC1vdXQtZ=
3JlYXQ_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTExNTIxX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291=
cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjExMTE1JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/60=
